URL reference: https://us.ovhcloud.com/resources/blog/kubernetes-audit-log-security-with-falco-on-ovhcloud-mks/
DateReviewed: 2026-06-09
Description: Today's article is a bit of a niche - looking at how to audit Kubernetes logs if you are using OVHcloud. While it's a bit specific, I think the overall lessons should still work, and they are using Falco for this, so let's take a peek. They start with a bit of motivating info, and then get to objectives - the biggest of which is tying your K8s deployment into a Logs data platform spot. This appears to be a raw VM, rather than a K8s deployment, and they walk you through the clicks needed to get it spun up. After it is running, you now have to create a reciever for the logs, which they call a data stream, and they walk you through setting that up. We then note the web socket address, which they say we'll use later. Now we have to point our K8s cluster at the log platform; they do this again through a web UI, but you oddly have to subscribe (where I think you'd want to publish). When this is done, we're feeding our log event stream into the platform, and now we have to set up Falco. They show us a YAML file to base thing on, and then how to use Helm to deploy Falco with the YAML we created. The request a new namespace, which is sensible, considering this is security stuff. They give us commands to monitor it starting up, and how to verify Falco is running right. To test Falco functionality, they show us how to add a simple rule detecting an exec or attach to a pod; and then after the rule is running, we exec to a pod. Well done walk through, if a little specific.
BottomLine: Good vendor specific example of using Falco to monitor Kubernetes
